    short: "Entrepreneur and grain industrialist, who opened the first automated technological mill in Europe in Stavropol — fed people in hungry years.",
    legacy: "Guliyev's mill in Stavropol and a network of steam mills in the North Caucasus and Transcaucasia, feeding millions of people.",
     bio: "Aga Bala Haji Gulu oglu Guliyev was born in 1862 in Baku into a poor family. From childhood, he helped his parents: he sold kutabs, baked by his mother, in the streets and bazaars, then worked at a mill and very early realized that the bread business could become not just trade, but a large industry. According to archival sources, already in his youth he worked at Tatosov's mill, where, thanks to his abilities and diligence, he was appointed manager, and having saved his first money, he bought an old mill in Baku and began to equip it with new technology. It was with this mill that the path of the man who was later called the «flour king» and «king of mills» began.\n\nBy the beginning of the 20th century, his mill was already generating hundreds of thousands, and then more than a million rubles a year, which put Guliyev among the largest entrepreneurs in the food industry of Baku. Later, his business network extended far beyond Baku. In the early 20th century, Guliyev had mills in Baku, Stavropol, and Georgievsk; the «Caucasian Joint-Stock Company of Flour and Rice Mills of A. B. Guliyev» he created controlled up to 70% of the flour milling industry of Stavropol by the beginning of the First World War.\n\nGuliyev's business empire covered a vast area — from Transcaucasia and Persia to southern Russia. His mills and trading offices operated in Tehran, where he supplied flour and grain to Persia; in Derbent, which became an important hub for Caspian grain trade; in Ganja (Elisavetpol), where the mill supplied flour to the entire western Transcaucasia; and in Kars, through which Guliyev's bread went to border areas and the army. Enterprises in southern Russia were of particular importance: in Rostov-on-Don, the main grain port of the empire, he had offices and warehouses connecting Don grain with Caucasian mills. And in Beslan, Guliyev launched one of his most ambitious projects — in 1913, he began construction of a large starch and molasses plant near Beslan station of the Vladikavkaz railway, in the village of Tulatovo, Vladikavkaz district, Terek region. The plant, which used local corn, became one of the largest enterprises of its kind in the North Caucasus and marked the beginning of Beslan's industrial development: a settlement grew around the production, jobs appeared, railway infrastructure and warehouses, and Beslan starch was supplied throughout Russia.\n\nBy the beginning of the First World War, Aga Bala Guliyev was not only a major miller but also a prominent wartime philanthropist: he participated in helping residents of the Kars region, supported the infirmary of the Baku city administration, helped families of mobilized Cossacks, and sent food to refugees. Flour from his enterprises went not only to the Caucasus but also to St. Petersburg, Moscow, Warsaw, Riga, Astrakhan, Rostov, and other cities of the empire.\n\nA special place in his biography is occupied by Stavropol. In 1908, Guliyev acquired Baranov's mill and virtually rebuilt it. The project was estimated at approximately 350–352 thousand silver rubles — a huge sum for that time. The enterprise acquired modern equipment, a powerful elevator, a railway branch, and even a German steam whistle, by which, as local sources wrote, Stavropol checked the time. This mill became one of the symbols of industrial Stavropol and the only industrial building in the city whose image was printed on postcards.\n\nAfter the establishment of Soviet power, Guliyev's fate changed dramatically. According to a widespread version, he died in Tabriz after 1920.",
