    short: "The main national collection of Russian painting, over 180,000 works.",
    full: "In 1856, 24-year-old merchant Pavel Tretyakov bought his first painting — «The Temptation» by K. Schilder — and set himself the goal of assembling a «Russian national gallery». Over forty years, he acquired almost all the most important paintings of his time: from V. Perov and I. Kramskoy to I. Repin, V. Surikov, and I. Levitan. In 1874, a special gallery building was added to his own house in Lavrushinsky Lane, and in 1892, Tretyakov donated a collection of 1287 paintings and 518 drawings to Moscow — at that time, it was the largest private donation in the history of the Russian Empire. Today, the Tretyakov Gallery houses over 180,000 works, has branches in Samara, Kaliningrad, and Vladivostok, and remains the foundation of the entire Russian art school — without it, neither the history of Russian art nor the self-awareness of national culture would be conceivable.",
